    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "(A slight, almost imperceptible twitch of the eye, as if a particularly loud squeak from a nearby goblin has startled you.)\n\nRight, right. HR advice. No rambling tales of subterranean mischief. Though, honestly, even the most rigid HR manual has a certain chaotic energy, much like a goblin horde deciding which direction to raid next.\n\nIf you are dealing with someone who is being *difficult to work with*—a behavioral issue, not just a skill gap—then you need to be very precise, and frankly, \"developmental opportunities\" can be dangerously vague when dealing with attitude.\n\n\"Needs improvement\" is clearer in a behavioral context because it forces specificity. If you say they \"need improvement\" in \"collaboration,\" you are signaling that their *interaction* with others is the problem. It’s a direct call-out to the behavior. It’s less about their inherent ability (like a goblin's knack for shiny things) and more about their execution in a team setting.\n\n\"Developmental opportunities\" is often better suited for technical skill gaps—like if a goblin apprentice can't properly sharpen a rusty axe. It suggests they just need more practice. When applied to difficult behavior, it",
      "source": "target",
